  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Submitting suspicious activity reports\n- Filing currency transaction reports\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Implementing internal policies and procedures\n- Training staff on detection and prevention\n- Maintaining comprehensive record-keeping\n\n4. Risk assessment\n- Identifying potential money laundering vulnerabilities\n- Developing risk mitigation strategies\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n\n5. Legal penalties\n- Potential fines for non-compliance\n- Criminal prosecution for willful misconduct\n- Potential loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar laws internationally. Financial institutions must actively work to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nFailure to comply can result in significant financial and legal consequences, making AML compliance a critical aspect of financial institution operations.",
